</ul>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="References">References</span></h2>
<p><b>Explanatory notes</b></p>
<div class="reflist" style="list-style-type: lower-alpha;">
<div class="mw-references-wrap">
<ol class="references">
<li id="cite_note-Maxwell-15"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-Maxwell_15-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><a href="#CITEREFMaxwellSwisher1897">Maxwell &amp; Swisher 1897</a>, p.&#160;431; <a href="#CITEREFBrannon1976">Brannon 1976</a>, p.&#160;258; and <a href="#CITEREFFederal_Writers.27_Project1937">Federal Writers' Project 1937</a>, p.&#160;33. Maxwell and Swisher assert the society's first two volumes were <a href="/wiki/Plutarch" title="Plutarch">Plutarch</a>'s <i><a href="/wiki/Parallel_Lives" title="Parallel Lives">Parallel Lives</a></i> and <a href="/wiki/Emer_de_Vattel" title="Emer de Vattel">Emer de Vattel</a>'s <i><a href="/wiki/The_Law_of_Nations" title="The Law of Nations">The Law of Nations</a></i>. However, the Federal Writers' Project and historian Selden W. Brannon state that the first two books purchased by the society were Plutarch's <i>Parallel Lives</i> and <a href="/wiki/Charles_Rollin" title="Charles Rollin">Charles Rollin</a>'s <i>Ancient History</i>.</span></li>
</ol>
